  "prompt": "Why have so many professional wrestlers died young?",
  "response": "The premature deaths of many professional wrestlers have been attributed to a variety of factors, although each case can be quite individual. Here are some commonly cited reasons:\n\n1. **Physical Demands and Injuries**: Wrestling is an extremely physically demanding profession, with performers dealing with frequent injuries and chronic pain. Many wrestlers endure significant physical strain, leading to long-term health issues.\n\n2. **Substance Abuse**: Pain management often leads some wrestlers to use prescription or recreational drugs, sometimes resulting in addiction or overdose. In addition, steroids and other performance-enhancing drugs were commonly used in wrestling, particularly in past decades, which can have severe long-term health consequences.\n\n3. **Mental Health Challenges**: The lifestyle can be extraordinarily stressful and isolating, with constant travel and little time for rest. This can lead to mental health struggles, including depression and anxiety, sometimes resulting in self-destructive behavior.\n\n4. **Cardiovascular Issues**: Large body sizes and potentially the use of substances like steroids can contribute to heart problems. Many wrestlers have died from heart attacks at relatively young ages.\n\n5. **Lack of Regular Medical Care**: Unlike athletes in some sports, wrestlers, particularly those on the independent circuit, may not have access to regular medical check-ups or proper health care, which can lead to undetected health issues.\n\n6. **Industry Changes**: Reporting on wrestler deaths has contributed to increased awareness and gradual changes within the industry to promote more sustainable lifestyles for performers. However, historical practices have left a lasting impact on the wellness of many.\n\nWhile these factors have historically contributed to the early deaths of some wrestlers, it\u2019s important to note that there have been industry changes aimed at improving the health and safety of wrestlers, from wellness policies to increased access to mental health resources.",
